@TheGeckoGuild Hi hello I adore Destiny 2 and have played through all the base game and expansion stories so if you ever want a pal to go shooting in space with or you want to ask about story/lore, I’m around! 👀

Oh, and yes, I’ve even asked my brother to help with fights even while I’m streaming. Chat gets to say hi to him, and he gets to show off his skills on stream.

So if you’re afraid that you’re less of a gamer for needing help, I’m here to say you’re not. You’re really not.

It doesn’t make me a cheater, or a wuss. I’d like to see those gatekeeping snobs try and play games while their joints are on fire and barely able to move.

And sometimes, I just don’t have the energy to do long fights. Narratives and lore are my gaming loves, not fights.

I get tired. I get sudden onsets of horrible chronic pain in my hands. When I’m too deep into a mission to exit it, I don’t want to have to redo it all. So I’ll check if my brother is free; if he is, I get him to clear something in 5 minutes that would have taken me much longer.
And here: https://t.co/RLpIrJQm82
As I said here 👇 https://t.co/Rxxfocpm7U

There’s no shame in asking someone to do a task for you in a video game. There are things I will always struggle with as a disabled gamer, especially since I play most games mainly one-handed. My brother is a beast at parts I find hard. It doesn’t mean I’m any less of a gamer.

Sometimes, when my hands are giving me trouble & there isn’t an accessibility option to solve it, I ask my brother to do a section in a video game. He’s quick, talented & it means I can move on in the story or mission.

I’m here to tell you it’s okay to ask for help when gaming.

I struggle to land the jumps in Destiny 2; I frequently accidentally blow myself up when my thumb suddenly spasms and shifts my aim. But if non-disabled players were told to only use one hand (and their thighs for the trigger buttons), I wonder if they’d struggle too 🤔

It’s funny. I make a ton of mistakes and silly moves in games; there’s always that voice in my head telling me I’ll never be a decent player.

But then a pal pointed out that I effectively play video games one-handed, and you know what? I’m a pretty good gamer in that respect! 💪

I couldn’t do that job again. Even if I wanted to. Of course, disabled people do work in service jobs. We always have, even when employment discrimination was/is legal. I do miss my colleagues sometimes. But any work I do now has to fit within the limits of my body and mind.

(And as much as I did enjoy the work, I do believe it contributed towards fibromyalgia rearing its head, down the line - and my chronic pain and fatigue worsening to the point I nearly left my master’s degree.)

It always irritates me when people look down on and devalue service industry jobs. It touches a nerve. Because I worked in that industry during university. I worked hard. And of all the work I’ve had since, McDonald’s pushed me the most mentally and physically. It was tough.

@joetomasone @NyessaGaming @Lenniesaurus your skill set in IT is different to the skill set of a cashier or cook, but the latter jobs still have skill sets. And not everyone can do those jobs. They’re regarded as easy jobs, and they’re not. I’ve had varied jobs, and McDonald’s was easily the hardest on my body and mind.

@joetomasone @NyessaGaming @Lenniesaurus Having been a McDonald’s cashier - it is ABSOLUTELY a skill. I’d like to see you try and handle a flood of rude customers in the middle of the lunch rush while their children scream. You have to juggle so many things in that job. It is hard. And it’s the opposite of unskilled.

I’m lucky. I grew up in a house filled to the brim with books. At its peak I think our combined book collection numbered 4000. I had a rare childhood in that respect. And I think it’s why I’m so bemused by this weird moral hysteria over books. I honestly don’t understand it.

UK schools have never had that moral panic about books in school that American ones have. Hell, the school librarians let me take out books that were strictly ‘17-18 only’ when I was 15. And no one batted an eyelid. The teachers knew me as a ‘voracious reader’ - their words.

Did I read Interview With The Vampire way too early? Probably. Did it scar me? Nope. If I didn’t like a book (and I knew if I did early on) I would just toss it aside. (But I ended up loving Anne Rice’s books, they were incredibly formative to me as a baby queer.)

I know this question is semi-rhetorical, but my parents never censored my reading and for that I’m profoundly grateful. It enabled me to make my own choices. Sure, Flowers is a weird AF book, but I didn’t ever feel the sense that I was reading something I shouldn’t. https://t.co/gUuFmBywZ0

So when Omicron eases and it’s safe to visit loved ones again - please hug them. Tell them you love them.

Covid has stolen so much from us all. Family, whether blood or found, is vital. And had I known February 2020 would be the last time he hugged me, I would have never let go.

I won’t post photos because I prefer to keep my family private, but he had a brilliant smile. It lit his eyes. And he had ash-blond hair that I always joked was always grey. (It had blond tints to it until the day he died, in his eighties, and he never once dyed it.)

Five months gone today.

It’s never enough time. We never get enough time.

I’d give anything to hear his laugh again. Hell, even his grumbling. I miss the strangest things about him some days.

I just wish my grandfather was still here.

2021 was so fucking hard.

This also counts for those GIFs or animated emotes that use intense motion blur; these can be just as dangerous as flashing. It’s never fun stumbling across any of those.

Aesthetic should never come before accessibility, and if you think being accessible means your content loses appeal… that’s not a good indication about your work!

It’s so easy to be more accessible. It doesn’t take much. Your disabled viewers will appreciate it. I know I will.

There are some fantastic creators I have to watch on audio-only for this reason. I hate it so much, because I feel like I’m missing a whole chunk of their work.

So, please do look at this from a disability and accessibility perspective. Flashing lights/colours can be dangerous!

There are a lot of streamers who use flashing light/colour imagery (including for alerts and scene transitions) and I just want to say: please reconsider.

It means people who are epileptic, seizure-prone, or migraine-prone like myself have to avoid your content, and that sucks!

Scratching the itches gives momentary relief - but then they hop to different parts of my body. I could scratch my knee and suddenly my forearm starts itching. Or I’m scratching my thigh yet then my upper back flares up.

It’s so hard to sleep when this happens. I rarely succeed.

When I have a flare like this, it also means I cannot stand having anything touching my skin, because it itches so, so much. And it is a pain to deal with in winter, because it’s too cold to not wear clothing. So finding the balance and coping is so hard.

Fibromyalgia is awful.

I’m having a really bad night with fibro-induced skin sensitivity, and I wish I could just lie in an ice-cold bath.

Most people think that fibromyalgia is just musculoskeletal pain, but it’s not. It’s so many things, and for me, it involves flare-ups of my skin being so itchy.

One thing the TikTok established was how little the creator actually knew about their ancestral country. They asked when had the Irish “ever actually suffered”, which, welp.

If you’re going to claim a country and its culture, please research. Please.

I did wonder if part of it was to do with not acknowledging whiteness as an identifier (and thereby disregarding systemic racism). Which, as a white person, seems very silly? Like. You’re white. https://t.co/lpAhMduVwf

For clarification: I’m talking about people who don’t immerse themselves in the culture of that country. 

For example, calling yourself Irish American with a great great great great Irish grandparent but knowing nothing about Irish culture or history.

@pictobeam I should have clarified - I meant those who say they’re Scottish (for example) but the only Scottish person in their family was their great great great grandparent and they don’t actually understand the culture. But you do have a connection to your familial culture.

From what I’ve seen and learnt about America, white Americans do have state-focused cultures. Each state has a wildly different identity. Like mini countries.

I guess I’m just trying to understand why cling to an old identity when you have a more obvious one?

And yes, I am acutely aware that the US was born out of colonialism, and maybe that’s why white Americans hold onto their heritage so tightly.

But if you have no connection to the land or the culture, what is it that makes you personally call yourselves Irish/Scottish?

Over here, your nationality is very much tied to culture and living/spending time *in* that country. It’s close and immediate. But I’m learning that a for lot of white Americans, nationality is tied to heritage and ancestry.

I’m wondering if white Americans and Europeans view the concept of heritage and nationality differently. The TikTok made me realise that it’s probably true, but I wanted to see what people here think.

So I saw a TikTok that got me thinking about nationality vs. ethnicity.

White Americans, why do you say you’re Irish/Scottish if your great great (and so on) grandparent was the last Irish or Scottish person in your family?

This is me being curious, not hostile.

My grandparents still used rotary phones until I was… 16? They had a beautiful black one in the living room, and I was fascinated by it, because rotary phones were dying out, so to speak. I still wonder what they did with theirs.

That tweet makes me want to show the younger generations old and obsolete tech. Not to laugh at them, but to educate.

After all, we’re reaching that point where they call it “the save icon” and don’t recognise that it’s a floppy disk.

I love the history of technology so much.

@cameron_kasky So there’s this thing called a landline, & physical note-writing. But honestly, I filled my time with books. I had pen pals who I wrote letters to.

It’s almost startling to see technology so ingrained in society yet still remember a time when it wasn’t. Seems a different world.

Should I listen to the original versions on YT to hear the differences between songs? Or should I just stick with Taylor’s Version?

I don’t know what the history behind Red’s creation is (though I have hunches, thanks Twitter), but it’s clear that it drove Taylor’s musical inspiration full speed. In doing so, gorgeous pieces were created.

Red (Taylor’s Version) is poignantly powerful. I need to listen again.

I can see why fans and critics consider All Too Well to be the emotional core of Red. It’s a beautiful piece; the extended version shook me to the core.

But it’s the carefree, amused sense of hindsight in songs like ‘We Are Never Ever Getting Back Together’ that I really love.

Experiencing Red for the first time, having never listened to the old version, has been a joy. There’s something poignant in a musician looking back a decade later over songs she wrote as a baby twenty-something.

There’s a maturity in Taylor’s voice. And it works so well.

I listened to Red for the 1st time today.

I don’t just mean the new Red.

I’d never listened to Red before. The first Taylor album I bought was 1989. I would have bought Red, but then the news about the masters broke. I decided to wait for Taylor’s Version.

I’m so glad I did.

Yes, I’m angry. No, I’m not going to apologise for it. Why should I apologise for wanting the most basic accommodations that take less than a minute to add?

Deaf/HoH people and people with cognitive disabilities watch streams too, you know. We deserve to enjoy them in full.

If you do forget, and you’re in the opening cutscenes? Go back to settings, turn subtitles on, then restart the game so that your viewers who need subtitles can enjoy the cutscenes as much as your viewers who don’t. That way, your disabled viewers don’t miss out on what happens.

I’m so tired of asking for basic considerations. It shouldn’t take you until the game’s started to turn the subtitles on. It should be an automatic thought.

It doesn’t take long to check the game’s options & make the dialogue accessible for disabled viewers. It really doesn’t.

It really hurts when it seems like streamers think it’s too much effort or too afraid it’ll be an inconvenience to stop a cutscene to add subtitles.

Because of course it’s just SO inconvenient to be accessible 🙄

I just missed out on understanding the opening cutscenes of a game because the streamer said the above statement.

This person could have easily gone back to settings, turned them on, then restarted the opening cutscenes. But they didn’t. They acted like it didn’t really matter.

Streamers, I have a very frustrated thing to say, as a disabled viewer.

Please, PLEASE turn on game subtitles BEFORE you start the game. 

Saying mid-cutscene “I should have turned them on, I’ll do it in a minute” and then just carrying on watching is NOT GOOD ENOUGH.

I’m drinking tea and even lifting my mug is tiring. Chronic fatigue, for me, is worse than chronic pain. Pain, I have meds and treatments for. But there’s no treatment for chronic fatigue. No way to banish it. Caffeine makes me even sleepier. (?!?!)

I’ve been awake an hour and I’m ready for bed. I’m just. So very tired. But it’s 1pm and if I sleep now then that fucks up the pitiful sleep schedule I have.

“If you can’t handle it, you need to grow up!”

Most people with early trauma grew up too fast.

These warnings make it easier for us to decide whether to continue or avoid something. It’s a moment of compassion in a world that sorely needs it.

“Trigger warning!”

okay but for WHAT???

if you don’t specify, it’s incredibly anxiety-inducing because we have no idea what you mean. Gore? Sexual violence? A possibility of seizures or migraines?

Please, please add a specification after the TW/CW.

It’s also not helpful to censor the word(s) itself, because if you do that, it won’t register as a muted word/phrase for whoever has the word/term muted.

TW fl*shing l*ghts = not helpful

A reminder that if you’re notifying about trigger/content warnings, it’s not enough to simply put TW or CW & nothing else. You have to specify the warnings, otherwise the TW/CW is useless.

I have a BA in History & a MSc in Medieval Literature. I write non-fiction pieces on disability & queerness. I love archives & records.  I create lists & spreadsheets for fun. I created the #DisabledStreamerDatabase.

I have a lot of transferable skills. I just need to get a job.

I’ll have to start part-time to get my body used to it. If my health doesn’t take a nose-dive, I hope to move to full-time. I WANT to work. I miss working.

So if anyone knows of a part time remote job, DM me? I have research, editing, critical analysis & creative writing skills.

With a remote job, I won’t have to waste precious energy commuting. I’ll be seated at a desk. I’ll struggle, but I won’t struggle nearly as much as I would a job that requires a both commute and for me to stand.

“But it’s illegal for companies to refuse to hire on the basis of disability!”

Sure it is, but it doesn’t stop them doing it. The only standard job I’ve ever held was one where I didn’t disclose my disabilities until AFTER they’d made the offer and I’d accepted.

I realise the last line makes it seem like I’ve only just started job hunting; in fact I’ve been looking for a while. The pandemic has brought far more remote jobs, which I could do as a disabled person. The issue is getting offers when you don’t keep your disabilities secret.

I’m not a trans woman or trans man. I don’t bear the brunt of the onslaught of hate that this government and the press aim towards trans people. Even so, as a non-binary person, the hate hurts.

Not everyone in the UK can come out. And we shouldn’t expect anyone to have to do so.

I’m very lucky to live in a country that has better queer acceptance and legal protections than many others - but the UK is its own brand of hell for queer folk. It’s called TERF Island for a reason. Even in 2021, it can be unsafe to come out here. I’m lucky, but others aren’t.

When you live in a society that still paints cisgender and straight as the norm, there will always be forms of coming out. People will assume I’m cis and straight. People will assume it in the way they ask if I have a boyfriend, and don’t also ask about a girlfriend or partner.

I had distinct comings-out - bisexual at 14, non-binary at 23 - but there’s always these:

“yeah, actually you do work with queer people, hi hello”
“yes, [relative], I’m gay”
“I like your [very queer apparel], I have that too!”

(the latter is always my favourite)
